title.narrative: CHILD PROTECTION PREVENTIVE SERVICES

description.narrative: Communities, parents, caregivers and children have increased awareness of the consequences of violence and have the skills to protect children and women., which contributes to Access To Justice, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, girls, boys and women nationally have increased access to and utilize preventive and responsive protection services that promote their safety, well-being and access to justice.

title.narrative: Communities, parents, caregivers and children have increased awareness of the consequences of violence and have the skills toprotect children and women.

description.narrative: To break the cycle of violence, UNICEF utilised an evidence-based two-pronged approach: i) understand the norms and attitudes that drive VAWG and VAC; and ii) utilise community engagement/communication for behaviour change initiatives and promote;parents and caregivers positive parenting skills to reduce child maltreatment in home settings. In 2021, 2591 parents (892 fathers, 1699 mothers) parents/caregivers have been trained in target provinces on the parenting for childhood development (P4CD) program, and 9,871 children (5382 boys and 4489 girls) benefited from improved parents&39; parenting skills. Since 2017, 30,060 community members, namely parents, community volunteers, facilitators and children, were recached and engaged. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:28/12/2021
